@Steve L

Continuing a conversation we started yesterday...

On my PC, it has always played the music the first time I solved the puzzle.  After that, if I went back into the puzzle, it would not play the music again.  Now when I go back into the puzzle, it plays the music again.

@Barry Ancona

I use the web version (on my phone browser) and it required them filled in - in fact twice, since I was pretty sure I had them in the first time.

Not that I could see either way, because of the terrible design / editing at play here.

@B
As far as I could tell, the Admire button has always done nothing. Glitsch or astringent commentary? You decide.

Seriously, what -- if anything -- did it ever do?

@SBK

It just brought you to the finished puzzle to view it.  ("Admire" it).  Useful for review when reading comments.

Now one has to click the X instead, which also seems to turn the timer running again, even though the puzzle is complete.  (I usually have the clock view turned off but have noticed this when I have it on.). It's really poorly designed and tested.

@B

I generally don't do the puzzle in the browser when I use my phone.  I use the app when I'm on the phone.

So that may be true.

@LARRY

Seems to be a common problem today.

Another technical triumph for the NYT Games department.

@LARRY 
Not sure which combo of apps, programs, or machinery you're using but try overtyping the little dancers with the letters they're replacing.
Worked for me.

@Stephen
I am only an average solver, and I found this puzzle much harder than Wednesday's used to be.  I needed nine cheats.

I do admire its cleverness, though.  Apparently by the time I got up, the technical difficulties have been solved.

@dutchiris

This isn't what we meant when we asked that the puzzles be again made "harder to solve"!

/monkey's paw

@Mike

I have noticed that it slowly refreshes the entire page (starting with the column view) every time I hit Reply to a post now, including here.   Sometimes drafts disappear.  The web/comment experience has gone significantly south quite recently.  It's as if some people with half baked ideas and no skills just took over everything.

Which I suppose is also a metaphor.

@Keep It Simple Please
The program now seems to have acquired a nervous tic whereby it shuts the comments page, pauses at the column  and then returns to the comments after some indeterminate interval.
Perhaps it needs psychotherapy to overcome this oscillation between hiding and display?

@Chris No wonder it threw me off. Rebus spaces are one of the most poorly implemented online puzzle ideas I've yet seen, and I spend a lot of time on Sporcle.

This puzzle had such great clues otherwise. I even learned today that a solo home run counts as a...well...that would be telling.

NYT, PLEASE, PLEASE, PLEASE fix the rebus interface or just delete it. I am angry that my subscription payment went in any part to help maintain it.

